50|$|Israel {{established}} West Jerusalem as {{its capital}} in 1950. The Israeli government needed to invest heavily to create employment, building new government offices, a new university, the Great Synagogue and the Knesset building. West <b>Jerusalem</b> <b>became</b> {{covered by the}} Law and Administrative Ordinance of 1948, subjecting West Jerusalem to Israeli jurisdiction.|$|R
50|$|On May 12, 1968, the {{government}} proclaimed a new holiday - Jerusalem Day - {{to be celebrated}} on the 28th of Iyar, the Hebrew date on which the divided city of <b>Jerusalem</b> <b>became</b> one. On March 23, 1998, the Knesset passed the Jerusalem Day Law, making the day a national holiday.|$|R
