50|$|Baldwin III (1130 - 10 February 1163) was King of Jerusalem from 1143 to 1163. He was {{the eldest}} son of Melisende and Fulk of <b>Jerusalem.</b> He <b>became</b> king while still a child, and was at first overshadowed by his mother Melisende, whom he {{eventually}} defeated in a civil war. During his reign <b>Jerusalem</b> <b>became</b> more closely allied with the Byzantine Empire, and the Second Crusade {{tried and failed to}} conquer Damascus. Baldwin captured the important Egyptian fortress of Ascalon, but also {{had to deal with the}} increasing power of Nur ad-Din in Syria. He died childless and was succeeded by his brother Amalric.|$|R
